tion until the authentication is validated. It can also be used as an authorization gateway if a particular credential fails to redirect. Being early in the pipeline, you can block it easily if needed."), mdx("p", null, "Jumping to post-middleware, the most obvious one is the middleware that normalizes the data. This middleware listens to all activities that have a role in saving data to the reducer. It will normalize the data and send multiple dispatches to reducers. I recommend sending one dispatch per entity type since you can have a lot of reducers that are doing different manipulation per type. Since you should have one reducer per entity, it makes sense to have a more granular dispatching process. In the end, reducers will benefit by having a simpler immutability logic that is targeted to the reducer itself."), mdx("p", null, "The last post-middleware can be a telemetry one where you may want to capture some actions for telemetry purposes. See this middleware as a logging middleware that avoids cluttering domain middleware."), mdx("h3", null, "Conclusion"), mdx("p", null, "This architecture is not fancy, making it shine by being easy to read and to change. If you have a new page to build, you only need to create your dummy React component, a middleware for the page if it\u2019s not from an existing domain and adjust the normalization and reducer (if new entities are required)."));
